To create an Amazon S3 bucket that can receive data from an application deployed in Amazon EKS, you can use the following Terraform script:
```hcl
provider "aws" {
  version = "4.54.0"
  region  = "us-west-2"
}

# Create a new S3 bucket
resource "aws_s3_bucket" "example" {
  bucket = "example-bucket-name"
  acl    = "private"
}

# Create an IAM policy to allow the EKS cluster to put objects into the S3 bucket
resource "aws_iam_policy" "eks_s3_policy" {
  name        = "eks_s3_policy"
  policy      = jsonencode({
  Version = "2012-10-17",
  Statement = [
    {
      Effect = "Allow",
      Action = [
        "s3:PutObject",
        "s3:PutObjectAcl",
        "s3:GetObject",
        "s3:ListBucket"
      ],
      Resource = "${aws_s3_bucket.example.arn}/*"
    }
  ]
})
}

# Attach the policy to the Amazon EKS Worker Node IAM role
resource "aws_iam_role_policy_attachment" "eks_s3_attach" {
  policy_arn = aws_iam_policy.eks_s3_policy.arn
  role       = "arn:aws:iam::<Your AWS Account ID>:role/aws-service-role/eks-worknode-node-<Your Nodegroup name>"
}
```
Replace `"example-bucket-name"` with the desired name for your S3 bucket. Replace `<Your AWS Account ID>` and `<Your Nodegroup name>` with your AWS account ID and the name of your EKS node group, respectively.

This script creates an S3 bucket with the name "example-bucket-name" and sets the bucket access control list (ACL) to "private". It also creates an IAM policy that allows the EKS cluster to put objects into the S3 bucket, get objects from the S3 bucket, and list the objects in the S3 bucket. Finally, it attaches the policy to the Amazon EKS Worker Node IAM role.

Note: Make sure you have the AWS CLI installed and configured with the proper AWS credentials and default region. Run `terraform init` to initialize your Terraform working directory, and run `terraform apply` to apply the configuration.

