A public member function in C++ is a function that is accessible from outside the class definition. In other words, it is a function that can be called by other parts of the program, outside of the class where it is defined.

Here's an example:
```
class MyClass {
public:
    void myPublicFunction() {
        cout << "This is a public function!" << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    MyClass myObject;
    myObject.myPublicFunction(); // This calls the public function
    return 0;
}
```
In this example, the function `myPublicFunction()` is declared as a public member function of the class `MyClass`. This means that it can be called by any part of the program that has access to an object of type `MyClass`.

In contrast, a private member function would only be accessible within the class where it is defined, and a protected member function would be accessible within the class and its derived classes.

