Yes, it is possible to clear the value of a ContentReference design attribute in a Salesforce Lightning Web Component (LWC) component. To do this, you can use the `componentSystem.triggerVisualForceRefresh()` method. This method will cause the component to refresh, which in turn will reset any data-bound attributes like a ContentReference design attribute.

Here's an example of how you can implement this in a custom LWC component:
```html
<!-- your-component.html -->
<template>
    <lightning-button onclick="clearContentReference()">Clear Content Reference</lightning-button>
</template>

<script>
    import { LightningElement, api, track } from 'lwc';

    export default class YourComponent extends LightningElement {
        @track contentReference;

        constructor() {
            super();
            this.contentReference = new ContentReference();
        }

        clearContentReference() {
            this.contentReference.setValue(null);
            api.surface.ibeacon.getInstance().componentSystem.triggerVisualForceRefresh();
        }
    }
</script>
```
Note that in this example, we're using a Lightning button to trigger the `clearContentReference()` method. This method clears the value of the `contentReference` design attribute by setting it to `null`. Finally, we call `componentSystem.triggerVisualForceRefresh()` to refresh the component, which will reset the attribute to its initial state.

