Here's a JavaScript function that calculates the intercept point between two rays, each defined by a point and an angle. The function takes four parameters: two points (x1, y1) and (x2, y2), and two angles (angle1, angle2). The angles should be in radians. The function returns the intercept point as an (x, y) pair or null if the rays are parallel and do not intersect.

```javascript
function findIntercept(x1, y1, angle1, x2, y2, angle2) {
  // If the angles are equal (or the slopes are equal), the rays are parallel
  if (angle1 === angle2) {
    return null;
  }

  // Calculate slopes (aka tangents of angles)
  const slope1 = Math.tan(angle1);
  const slope2 = Math.tan(angle2);

  // Calculate intercepts: b = y - mx
  const intercept1 = y1 - slope1 * x1;
  const intercept2 = y2 - slope2 * x2;

  // Calculate intersection point: x = (b2 - b1) / (m1 - m2)
  const x = (intercept2 - intercept1) / (slope1 - slope2);

  // Calculate y-coordinate of intersection point
  const y = slope1 * x + intercept1;

  return { x, y };
}
```

Here's an example of how to use the function to find the intercept point between two rays:

```javascript
const x1 = 1, y1 = 1;
const angle1 = Math.PI / 4;

const x2 = 5, y2 = 2;
const angle2 = -Math.PI / 4;

const intercept = findIntercept(x1, y1, angle1, x2, y2, angle2);

if (intercept) {
  console.log(`Intercept point: (${intercept.x}, ${intercept.y})`);
} else {
  console.log("The rays are parallel and do not intersect.");
}
```

