To analyze the sentiment of a poem in Go, you can use a natural language processing library or a third-party API. Since you requested an example using the IBM Watson Tone Analyzer API, here's an alternative approach with that API:

```go
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "os"

    "github.com/watson-developer-cloud/go-sdk/toneanalyzerv3"
    "github.com/watson-developer-cloud/go-sdk/core"
)

func main() {
    authenticator := &core.IamAuthenticator{
        ApiKey: "YOUR_API_KEY",
    }

    service, serviceErr := toneanalyzerv3.NewToneAnalyzerV3(&toneanalyzerv3.ToneAnalyzerV3Options{
        Authenticator: authenticator,
        Version:       "2017-09-21",
    })

    if serviceErr != nil {
        panic(serviceErr)
    }

    poem := `Looking out the window,
Seeing the beautiful blue sky.
My heart begins to fill with joy,
Almost in a state of bliss.`

    toneInput := &toneanalyzerv3.ToneInput{
        Text: &poem,
    }

    tone, _, responseErr := service.Tone(&toneanalyzerv3.ToneOptions{
        ToneInput: toneInput,
    })

    if responseErr != nil {
        panic(responseErr)
    }

    if tone.DocumentTone != nil {
        fmt.Println("Detected tones in the poem:")
        for _, tone := range tone.DocumentTone.Tones {
            fmt.Printf("Tone: %s, Score: %f\n", *tone.ToneName, *tone.Score)
        }
    } else {
        fmt.Println("No detected tones.")
    }
}
```

Make sure to replace "YOUR_API_KEY" with your own API key. This code uses the IBM Watson Tone Analyzer API to detect present tones in the poem. The response can be used to examine sentiment or emotion conveyed throughout the text.

